AGI -&nbsp; "Cauto optimism">. The same expression is used both from Russia and the United States > to describe the prospects of a ceasefire in Ukraine > after the night interview at the Kremlin between the Russian President, Vladimir Putin, and the White House envoy, Steve Witkoff. "Cauto optimism" Putin accepts the thirty-day truce proposed by the US was expressed last night by the American National Security Councilman, Mike Waltz, to Fox's microphones.
And of "regions justifying a cautious optimism" spokesman of the Russian presidency, Dmitry Peskov. "But there is still a lot to do," Peskov warned, echoing the conditions put by Putin, in the first place to prevent Kiev from taking advantage of the ceasefire to rearm.
<div </div
A new phone call between Putin and the American colleague, Donald Trump, now seems imminent, has allowed Peskov to be understood. First, however, Witkoff will have to relate Trump to his encounter with Putin and the messages that the Russian president intended to convey through him. The president of the United States, in a post on Truth Social, spoke of "very positive and productive debates" and "a great chance that this horrible and bloody war can finally end."
Trump then appealed to the Moscow colleague to save the lives of the Ukrainian soldiers "circulated" in the Kursk, > where Russian troops continue to advance. The Kursk question appears crucial in the conduct of negotiations. The Ukrainians last summer had occupied some areas of the Russian region to use them as exchange goods at the negotiating table. Now, however, the situation on the field is clearly favorable to Russia and Putin has made it clear that he intends to dislodge Ukrainians from Kursk before interrupting hostilities, so that he can deal with an even greater force position.
The Russian President "is now doing everything he can to sabotage diplomacy by putting extremely difficult and unacceptable conditions already from the beginning, even before a ceasefire", accuses the Ukrainian president, Volodymyr Zelensky, but I am sure that America has the " sufficient force" to force him to peace. "They serve strong initiatives," Zelensky concludes, "a strong pressure must be applied to the only one who wants to continue this war." &nbsp;
<h2>Putin, we will save troops in the Kursk if they surrender
Russia will save the lives of the Ukrainian soldiers surrounded by Russian troops in Kursk if Kiev will give them the order to depose the weapons. Russian President Vladimir Putin said this by responding to Donald Trump's call not to infier on the forces trapped in the sack conquered in Russian territory. "To effectively implement the appeal of the President of the United States, it is necessary an order from the political-military leadership of Ukraine to its military units: to lay down arms and surrender," said Putin speaking to the Russian Security Council, as reported by the Tass.
